artifacts.title: SaaS Product Strategic Analysis from Carlotta Interview
artifacts.summary: Comprehensive analysis revealing that profile depth is the load-bearing wall of the SaaS revenue model, identifying pre-booking OFFLINE_GAP (users google therapists before booking) as a critical funnel leak not addressed by current roadmap sequencing.
artifacts.persistence_evidence: Roadmap updated in Notion Brain via task b76deb1; Active Context updated. However, the full strategic analysis document with confidence levels, sequencing problem framing, and Audi/Mazda principle was delivered in conversation but not explicitly saved as a standalone strategic doc.
artifacts.content_excerpt: The SaaS strategy doc says 'One click to be a therapist' — replace the entire tool stack. But the Carlotta interview says the surface is the pipe. The surface IS the conversion mechanism. She saw 3 therapists, none matched her method, the profiles were too thin to form a 'Gefühl', and her instinct was to leave and google them. That's the OFFLINE_GAP starting at the directory, not at the booking. Profile depth isn't a polish item — it's the load-bearing wall of the SaaS revenue model.

artifacts.title: Testing Strategy Framework - Integration vs Mocks
artifacts.summary: Framework explaining why mocks failed to catch EARTH-294 bugs, with test layer mapping table and the principle that integration code must be tested against real external systems.
artifacts.persistence_evidence: Integration testing rules added to CLAUDE.md (committed to main); meta-learning recorded in MEMORY.md; testing guide created at docs/private/cal-multiformat-testing-guide.md
artifacts.content_excerpt: The gap is structural, not a coverage oversight. The existing tests are unit/API tests that mock Supabase. The 4 bugs lived in upgradeSchedule.ts which talks directly to Cal.com's Railway PostgreSQL via raw SQL. They were integration bugs. None of these are testable with mocks. A mock would encode your assumptions — the same assumptions that were wrong. For integration code that talks to external systems, test against the real system.

artifacts.title: EUIPO Trademark Conflict Analysis - KAUFMANN HEALTH
artifacts.summary: Comprehensive eSearch conflict assessment showing zero exact matches for 'KAUFMANN HEALTH' and analysis of 7 partial 'KAUFMANN' marks in Classes 35/42/44, concluding no blocking conflicts exist.
artifacts.persistence_evidence: Konban task 22ab2e4a-2d15-8007-9c55-d2d191df33fb updated with decision and next steps; user confirmed 'Update Konban' and assistant logged the analysis
artifacts.content_excerpt: Exact Match: 'KAUFMANN HEALTH' - 0 results. Completely clear. Partial Match: 'KAUFMANN' - 33 results, only ~7 active/registered with class overlap. SUSANNE KAUFMANN (Class 44, cosmetics) is the only mark worth watching but opposition risk is very low (~5%). All others in Classes 42/35 are unrelated industries (construction, architecture, law, fashion).

artifacts.title: Trademark Class Recommendation - Classes 35+42+44
artifacts.summary: Strategic decision to file EU trademark in all three classes (35, 42, 44) at EUR 1,050 total, with reasoning that Class 35 marketplace protection is essential for KH's business model and costs 6x more to add later.
artifacts.persistence_evidence: Logged to Konban Markenschutz task; user confirmed 'I'll bite the bullet on 1050 EUR' and requested Konban update
artifacts.content_excerpt: Recommendation: File all 3 classes. EUR 1,050. Class 35 isn't optional - KH IS a marketplace (therapists list → patients find them → KH takes a cut). Adding Class 35 later = new application = EUR 900 minimum. Adding it now = EUR 150 extra. You'd be paying 6x more for the same protection by waiting.
